- See [Code Quality Standards](mdc:consistency-senior-dev.mdc#code-quality-standards) for implementation guidelines
- See [Pattern Updates](mdc:consistency-patterns.mdc#pattern-updates) for evolving patterns

Follow these guidelines to create code that behaves predictably and intuitively.

## Core Principles

- Write code that behaves as other developers would expect
- Follow established patterns in the codebase
- Use clear, descriptive names that indicate behavior
- Avoid hidden side effects
- Keep similar things similar

## Naming Guidelines

- Name things based on what they do, not how they do it
- Use consistent terminology throughout the codebase
- Follow established naming patterns in the ecosystem
- Make boolean variables ask a question (isLoading, hasError)
- Use verb-noun format for functions (getData, updateUser)

## Function Behavior

> 📝 See [Senior Developer Guidelines - Code Quality Standards](mdc:.cursor/rules/consistency-senior-dev.mdc#code-quality-standards) for implementation details.

- Functions should do what their name suggests
- Return types should be consistent with function names
- Handle errors in expected ways
- Follow established patterns for async operations
- Keep function signatures consistent within categories

## Component Patterns

> 📝 See [React Best Practices](mdc:.cursor/rules/react-best-practices.mdc) for detailed React component guidelines.

- Props should behave like HTML attributes where applicable
- Follow React conventions for event handlers (onClick, onChange)
- Use consistent patterns for loading and error states
- Follow established patterns for form handling
- Keep component APIs consistent within categories

## State Management

- State updates should be predictable
- Follow established patterns for state management
- Use consistent patterns for loading states
- Handle errors in expected ways
- Keep state structure consistent

## API Design

> 📝 See [Tech Stack Documentation - Development Workflow](mdc:.cursor/rules/tech-stack.mdc#development-workflow) for API development process.

- Follow REST conventions where applicable
- Use consistent response formats
- Handle errors in expected ways
- Follow established patterns for authentication
- Keep API signatures consistent

## Internationalization

> 📝 See [Tech Stack Documentation - Internationalization](mdc:.cursor/rules/tech-stack.mdc#internationalization-i18n) for complete i18n setup.

- Use consistent translation keys across similar features
- Follow established patterns for pluralization
- Keep translation keys close to their usage
- Use descriptive keys that match content
- Handle fallbacks predictably

## Examples

```typescript
// ✅ Predictable naming and behavior
function getUserData(userId: string) {
  return fetchData(`/users/${userId}`);
}

// ❌ Surprising behavior
function getUser(userId: string) {
  deleteOtherData(); // Unexpected side effect
  return fetchData(`/users/${userId}`);
}

// ✅ Predictable component props
function Button({ onClick, disabled, children }) {
  return (
    <button onClick={onClick} disabled={disabled}>
      {children}
    </button>
  );
}

// ❌ Surprising component behavior
function Button({ action, inactive, content }) {
  return (
    <button onClick={() => setTimeout(action, 1000)} disabled={!inactive}>
      {content}
    </button>
  );
}
```

## Common Patterns

### Loading States

```typescript
// ✅ Consistent loading pattern
const { data, isLoading, error } = useQuery(...)

// ❌ Surprising loading pattern
const { data, loading, failure } = useQuery(...)
```

### Error Handling

```typescript
// ✅ Predictable error handling
try {
  await saveData();
} catch (error) {
  handleError(error);
}

// ❌ Surprising error handling
try {
  await saveData();
} catch {
  // Silently ignore errors
}
```

### State Updates

```typescript
// ✅ Predictable state update
setState((prev) => ({ ...prev, updated: true }));

// ❌ Surprising state update
setState((prev) => {
  delete prev.something; // Mutating state
  return prev;
});
```
